  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including China, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2006 and has been amended to strengthen its provisions. The law establishes a comprehensive framework to prevent and combat money laundering activities, including requirements for financial institutions to report suspicious transactions, maintain records, and implement internal controls.\n\nInternationally, money laundering is also recognized as a criminal offense under various treaties and conventions, such as the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (the Palermo Convention) and the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations. Countries that are part of these agreements are required to implement laws and regulations to combat money laundering effectively.\n\nEngaging in money laundering can result in severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, and confiscation of assets.",
